data.title: iWinTrusted.exe Windows process
data.meta_description: Windows 10/11/7 doesn't need iWinTrusted.exe. Click here to know if iWinTrusted is safe and how to avoid iWinTrusted.exe errors.
data.text:
What is iWinTrusted.exe?

The genuine iWinTrusted.exe file is a software component of iWinGames Application by iWin.

iWinTrusted.exe is part of the iWinGames Application. This is not an essential Windows process and can be disabled if known to create problems.

iWin is a large online developer, publisher and distributor of casual games for the mass market. iWin.com receives millions of visitors every month. They offer services such as downloadable games and online multiplayer games. iWin generates revenue through online and in-game advertising.

iWinTrusted stands for iWin Trusted Games Service

The .exe extension on a filename indicates an executable file. Executable files may, in some cases, harm your computer. Therefore, please read below to decide for yourself whether the iWinTrusted.exe on your computer is a Trojan that you should remove, or whether it is a file belonging to the Windows operating system or to a trusted application.

Click to Run a Free Scan for iWinTrusted.exe related errors

IWinTrusted.exe file information

The process known as iWin Trusted Games Service or iWinTrusted belongs to software iWinGames Application or iWin Games downloads and organizes your by iWin (www.iwin.com).

Description: IWinTrusted.exe is not essential for the Windows OS and causes relatively few problems. IWinTrusted.exe is located in a subfolder of "C:\Program Files (x86)"—e.g. C:\Program Files (x86)\iWin Games\. Known file sizes on Windows 10/11/7 are 223,472 bytes (27% of all occurrences), 176,848 bytes and 4 more variants.

It runs as background service iWinTrusted: iWin Trusted Game Service.

The program is not visible. The file has a digital signature. IWinTrusted.exe is not a Windows system file. IWinTrusted.exe is able to monitor applications. Therefore the technical security rating is 34% dangerous.

Uninstalling this variant: If there are any problems with iWinTrusted.exe, you can completely remove iWin Games or MSN Games (Control Panel ⇒ Uninstall a Program).

Recommended: Identify iWinTrusted.exe related errors

Important: Some malware camouflages itself as iWinTrusted.exe, particularly when located in the C:\Windows or C:\Windows\System32 folder. Therefore, you should check the iWinTrusted.exe process on your PC to see if it is a threat. We recommend Security Task Manager for verifying your computer's security. This was one of the Top Download Picks of The Washington Post and PC World.

Best practices for resolving iWinTrusted issues

A clean and tidy computer is the key requirement for avoiding problems with iWinTrusted. This means running a scan for malware, cleaning your hard drive using 1cleanmgr and 2sfc /scannow, 3uninstalling programs that you no longer need, checking for Autostart programs (using 4msconfig) and enabling Windows' 5Automatic Update. Always remember to perform periodic backups, or at least to set restore points.

Should you experience an actual problem, try to recall the last thing you did, or the last thing you installed before the problem appeared for the first time. Use the 6resmon command to identify the processes that are causing your problem. Even for serious problems, rather than reinstalling Windows, you are better off repairing of your installation or, for Windows 8 and later versions, executing the 7DISM.exe /Online /Cleanup-image /Restorehealth command. This allows you to repair the operating system without losing data.

To help you analyze the iWinTrusted.exe process on your computer, the following programs have proven to be helpful: ASecurity Task Manager displays all running Windows tasks, including embedded hidden processes, such as keyboard and browser monitoring or Autostart entries. A unique security risk rating indicates the likelihood of the process being potential spyware, malware or a Trojan. BMalwarebytes Anti-Malware detects and removes sleeping spyware, adware, Trojans, keyloggers, malware and trackers from your hard drive.
